  en: {
    h1: 'Is Your Organisation Ready for the EU Pay Transparency Directive?',
    metaTitle: 'EU Pay Transparency Directive Compliance Audit | EuroSalary.eu',
    metaDesc: 'Get a comprehensive EU Pay Transparency Directive compliance audit. Identify gaps, build a remediation roadmap, and meet the June 2026 transposition deadline.',
    home: 'Home', enterprise: 'Enterprise', breadcrumb: 'Transparency Audit',
    introAnswer: 'The EU Pay Transparency Directive requires all member states to transpose its requirements into national law by June 7, 2026. Our compliance audit identifies your gaps and provides a clear roadmap to full readiness across all operating countries.',
    tldr: [
      'EU Pay Transparency Directive must be transposed by June 7, 2026 — less than 14 months away',
      'Covers pay reporting, job posting transparency, right to information, and gender pay gap disclosure',
      'Our audit provides a country-by-country compliance gap analysis with prioritised remediation steps',
    ],
    heroSubtitle: 'The directive introduces the most significant change to EU compensation practices in decades. Organisations that prepare now will avoid costly retroactive compliance and potential penalties of up to 5% of annual turnover.',
    urgencyTitle: 'Critical Deadlines You Cannot Miss',
    urgencyDesc: 'The EU Pay Transparency Directive (2023/970) has firm deadlines that are approaching fast. Non-compliance exposes organisations to financial penalties, reputational damage, and employee litigation risk.',
    deadlineCards: [
      { date: 'June 7, 2026', desc: 'Member states must transpose the directive into national law. After this date, all requirements become enforceable regardless of whether national legislation is complete.' },
      { date: 'June 7, 2027', desc: 'First reporting period begins for organisations with 150+ employees. Gender pay gap reports must cover the previous calendar year.' },
      { date: 'June 7, 2031', desc: 'Reporting threshold drops to organisations with 100+ employees. Full pay transparency requirements apply across all member states.' },
    ],
    checklistTitle: 'Compliance Checklist — What the Directive Requires',
    checklistDesc: 'The EU Pay Transparency Directive introduces comprehensive requirements across four key areas. Our audit evaluates your readiness in each.',
    checklistItems: [
      { title: 'Pay Reporting Obligations', desc: 'Organisations must report gender pay gap data including mean and median pay gaps, bonus gaps, and the proportion of male vs female employees in each pay quartile. Reports must be filed with the national equality body.', icon: 'assessment' },
      { title: 'Job Posting Transparency', desc: 'All job postings must include the starting salary or salary range. Employers cannot ask candidates about their salary history. This applies to both internal and external job postings.', icon: 'work' },
      { title: 'Right to Information', desc: 'Employees have the right to request information about their individual pay level and the average pay levels broken down by sex for categories of workers performing the same work or work of equal value.', icon: 'info' },
      { title: 'Joint Pay Assessments', desc: 'Where pay reporting reveals a gender pay gap of 5% or more in any category that cannot be justified by objective gender-neutral criteria, the employer must conduct a joint pay assessment with worker representatives.', icon: 'groups' },
      { title: 'Pay Structure Transparency', desc: 'Employers must make available the criteria used to determine pay, pay levels, and pay progression. These criteria must be objective and gender-neutral.', icon: 'account_tree' },
      { title: 'Burden of Proof & Penalties', desc: 'The burden of proof in pay discrimination cases shifts to the employer. Member states must establish penalties that are effective, proportionate, and dissuasive — up to 5% of annual gross turnover.', icon: 'gavel' },
    ],
    formTitle: 'Request Your Compliance Audit',
    formDesc: 'Tell us about your organisation and we will deliver a comprehensive EU Pay Transparency Directive compliance assessment with country-specific remediation roadmap.',
    formLabels: {
      name: 'Full Name', email: 'Work Email', company: 'Company Name',
      countries: 'EU Countries of Operation', awareness: 'Compliance Deadline Awareness',
      submit: 'Request Compliance Audit',
    },
    awarenessOptions: [
      'Fully aware — actively preparing',
      'Aware but not yet started',
      'Partially aware — need guidance',
      'Not aware of the directive',
    ],
    successMsg: 'Thank you! Our compliance team will contact you within 48 hours.',
    faq: [
      { question: 'When does the EU Pay Transparency Directive take effect?', answer: 'The directive (2023/970) was adopted on May 10, 2023 and must be transposed into national law by all EU member states by June 7, 2026. Some member states may implement earlier. After the transposition date, requirements become enforceable even if a member state has not yet passed national legislation, under the doctrine of direct effect.' },
      { question: 'Which organisations are affected?', answer: 'All employers in EU member states are affected, regardless of size. However, pay reporting obligations phase in by size: organisations with 250+ employees from June 2027, 150+ from June 2027, and 100+ from June 2031. Job posting transparency and right to information requirements apply to all employers from transposition date.' },
      { question: 'What are the penalties for non-compliance?', answer: 'Member states must establish penalties that are effective, proportionate, and dissuasive. The directive specifically states that penalties should include fines that may be based on the employer annual gross turnover. Several member states are expected to set penalties at up to 5% of annual turnover, mirroring the GDPR penalty structure.' },
      { question: 'Does the directive apply to non-EU companies with EU employees?', answer: 'Yes. Any organisation that employs workers in EU member states is subject to the directive requirements in those member states. This includes companies headquartered outside the EU that have subsidiaries, branches, or remote employees in EU countries.' },
      { question: 'How does EuroSalary help with compliance?', answer: 'Our compliance audit provides a country-by-country gap analysis, identifying where your current pay structures, reporting processes, and job posting practices fall short of the directive requirements. We deliver a prioritised remediation roadmap with estimated timelines and resource requirements. Our enterprise platform then provides ongoing compliance monitoring and automated reporting capabilities.' },
    ],
  },
